<BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">quote:</font><HR>Horrible idea...<BR>And heres why.<P>1) then you could have a level 50 pet AND Mind flay. this is too much.<P>2) or you could have a level 50 pet and both your highest stacking DOTs, also too much.<P>3) And here si the biggest reason... it is a band aid approach. It slightly remedys the situation, but not not cure the cause. We don;t need to be able to ignopre mind, like so many have matter for so long. Then how varied woudl Sorcerors be? Not all all. They woudl ALL be full body, the rest matter.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>This is NOT a horrible idea.</B><P>1st Off) We all know a level 50 pet is not truly a level 50 pet.<P>2nd) Not all level 50 pets are created equally...many just plain suck.<P>3rd)Its damn near impossible to actually find a level 50 pet & a level 46 (yellow) pet is 100% worthless for offense...only use is for aggro management against guards & in PvE.<P>4th) Pets, in general(though especially charmed pets), are not very usefull in many RvR situations & are easily avoided by any RvR-Seasoned opponent.  The only thing they are really good for is kiting while you run away during a 1-on-1 fight, but then you usually lose your pet & have to get another, and we all know how much time that takes.<P>Here's the deal...IDEALLY if we get a GOOD level 50 pet, it is more powerful than most summoned pets.  However, there is a tradeoff for that power...though our pet MAY SOMETIMES be better, we have to travel long distances to get it, risk XP-death to get it, and we will lose it if we die or it dies, then we have to do it all over again.  Though I hate spending 30minutes getting a pet, I think the summoned-vs-charmed tradeoff is relatively balanced...we get a little more firepower, while summoning classes get consistancy & instant gratification with no risk.  I still think that we get the short end of the stick on that tradeoff, but for my personal playstyle, I can live with that.<P>What is NOT fair is that most summoning classes get their pet (which is as good or better than ours, considering the above) in their base line, while we have to spend nearly 1/2 of all of our spec points to get ours...even if we don't want AE Mez & AE Debuffs from the mind line.<P>I don't think of this as a "bandaid fix."  This is something that should have been considered from the start, and has nothing to do with the current uselessness of our Mind Spec Line.<P>If you disagree with that, then I propose we do this...lets look at the usefulness of our our mind BASE line.<BR>- Single Target Mez - Good spell, but seriously nerfed.<BR>- Amnesia - Generally worthless for both RvR & PvE...yes, you CAN find ways to use it, but why would you?<BR>- Confuse - Useful for unique situations in PvE, like getting mobbed in Dartmoor.  Generally not useful in PvE.  Useless in RvR.<P>Basically 3 spells in our Mind Base line, and none of them can be used regulary (though the mez would be used if someone were NOT specced in Mind).<P>Is this Base Line, balanced compared to other classes Class-Specific Base Lines?  I don't think so.  A base line charm WOULD make it useful & attractive.  If our pets are going to be debuffed, add pet buffs/heals in the spec line similar to cabbys.<P>--------------------<P><B>Quote 7/2/02 - i3ullseye, Sorcerer Team Lead: Actually no, i am not 'your' representative. this has been stated before. many TLs do not post ANYWHERE except the pendragn boards. Noone has to try to get ANY feedback from the general populace.</B><P><B>**********************</B><P>Palomides / Alat-Seldi<BR>Mezmo - Level 50.1 Sorcerer<BR>Tagalong - Level 41 Enhance Cleric<BR>Siege - Level 33 Armsman<BR>Terrenus - Level 28 Earth Wizard<BR>Miracle - Level 11 Rejuv Cleric<BR>Recurve - Level 10 Scout
